Modular Programming

Lead Developer: Jonathon Mellor


Learning Objectives

The aim of this course is for participants to:

  • Understand why code should be structured, and how modules help with this
  • Be aware of different styles of programming
  • Understand the important considerations when converting code into functions
  • Be able to take into account the requirements when splitting code up across files
  • Be able to write code as functions then modules and to import them

Target Audience

This course is designed for both python and R users.

This course assumes basic programming knowledge in the participants preferred language. Having completed an introductory course, or having experience in analysis would count.

This course in intended to improve the participants programming practices by showing how to structure code. It assumes the participant can already:

  • Work with dataframes (load and manipulate)
  • Perform basic data analysis (summary statistics)
  • Write simple functions to perform tasks

Introduction

This course will show you how to convert code into functions and modules so that the program can be structured and more reproducible.

To do this the course will go through a case study example where we refactor (re-structure) the existing code example. During this we will highlight key concepts and consideration when designing code.

Why structure code?

When writing programs it is often easy to fall into the trap of focusing on just achieving the final output.

For example you may be trying to:

  • Calculate a value
  • Produce a certain plot
  • Change some datas format

When completing tasks like this, it is often quickest to just write the code in a single file or notebook, working through each step until you meet the final goal.

By doing this the specific final goal is achieved, but how we got there is often unclear, difficult to re-run and hard to expand to new tasks.

You may have come across python and R files which do crucial work, but are thousands of lines long with no clear order. These types of files and notebooks become really difficult to understand as they get bigger. The time spent scrolling through the files, looking for variables all over the place could be better spent working on other tasks.

To combat this; functions, modules and packages can be used to structure programs making them more readable, easier to fix and simpler to add new features to.

A module is a file that contains one or more units of code - in our case functions. Multiple module files can be collected together to form a package.

You have likely already been using functions, modules and packages - they have just been written by other people. For example pandas and dyplyr are both packages which contain modules and functions.

By building all your code into functions, modules and packages, you can test each component of the code to be sure it performs as expected. Testing functions is called Unit Testing - a concept covered in further courses.

To show how to structure code in an analysis context we will use an example scenario to go through the steps taken.

Introducing the case study

You have been assigned to a new group within your department responsible for analysis populations across the world in collaboration with the United Nations.

Your job is to provide the analysis of population densities across the different United Nation Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) regions.

One of your colleagues has already conducted this analysis on an ad hoc basis previously. They have given you their code to start with. They only had to analyse one year of data, but you have been asked to write code that will be able to analyse multiple years of data, which are all in different files.

You decide before trying to tackle the big task of analysing all the data, you are going to refactor (re-structure) your colleagues code into functions and modules to make the task managable, and more reproducible in the future.

You have been given two data sets needed to reproduce the analysis your collegue performed. Have a look through the data, what considerations do you think need to be take into account to make the data analysable?

Programming Styles

Before getting started on the task of analysing the population density data, it is important that we are aware of different styles of programming.

Basic Programs

Scripts and notebooks can be really useful tools for quick analysis, however, they limit how we can scale and improve our project.

When writing basic programs we use variables to store the data we want at each step of the program.

Our scripts become one line after another of data being slightly changed at each step. This is done by overwriting the original variable or creating a new one. This does not group the code in a structure helpful for us to understand.

This style of programming is sometimes refered to as imperative.

When we need to reuse similar code the programmer ends up copy and pasting code to reuse it in different parts of the program with minor changes.

If the requirements of our project change, we need to hunt through the code to change all the relevant variables and values.

To expand the project we need to keep writing more and more code in the same file making it even harder to work through and understand.

Grouping Code

In order to structure our code better we need to be able to group a collection of code together into one object. This can be done in two ways:

  • Converting to functions
  • Converting to classes

Classes are beyond the scope of this course and less prevelant in R, so we will focus on functions although many principles are the same.

Properties of functions:

  • Functions complete tasks, preferably just one
  • Functions can take inputs and give outputs, but dont have to

Once the collections of code are made into functions we can run the function in one line rather than all the code in collection within.

If we have a well made function we dont need to know the details of what is happening inside it. Ideally we have functions whose name tells us exactly what they are doing. This means when we use the function it does what we expect it to.


There are two main styles we will discuss in this section which help us think about how to structure our code.

Here is an example piece of code we will be converting into the different styles. As its a small piece of code it is quite simple, so writing functions for it may be a bit of overkill, but this is just done to demonstrate the approaches.

The code:

  • takes a list of strings
  • lowercases all of the strings
  • remove the character "_" from all strings
  • it then adds a space " " at the end of each string

Try run it yourself to see what it does, or even write it yourself.

Python

initial_strings = ["_HELLO_", "there_", ",", "yOU", "ar_e", "Ah", "b_old", "1"]

# Lowercase each string
lowercase_strings = []
for each_string in initial_strings:
    lowercase_strings.append(each_string.lower())

# Remove strings with "_"
lower_without_uscore_strings = []
for each_string in lowercase_strings:
    lower_without_uscore_strings.append(each_string.replace("_", ""))

# append space to each list element
lower_without_uscore_space_strings = []
for each_string in lower_without_uscore_strings:
    lower_without_uscore_space_strings.append(each_string + " ")


print(lower_without_uscore_space_strings)
## ['hello ', 'there ', ', ', 'you ', 'are ', 'ah ', 'bold ', '1 ']

R

Style Examples

Procedural Style

Procedural code is a set of instructions run one after another. Each instruction is wrapped inside a function. The functions are called step by step.

Iteration is a common feature of procedural code, just like in the previous example.

Each step the result of the previous step is given to the next function.

This style is very common in python and R code.


All of the instructions are written as functions, these define what will happen when variables are given to them. Typically these are defined first in the file.

Below the functions is the code which runs the script. Each line executes one after the other, with data being passed from one function to the next.

To see what the program does we just need to look at the end of the code, each function describes how it changes the data it is given.


If we wanted to change the behaviour of any step, we would just change the relevant function.

If we wanted to perform the steps in a different order, we would just change the order in which they are run at the end of the script.

Python

## Define functions to achieve each step
def lowercase_all(strings):
    """Lowercase each string in the list"""
    lowercase_strings = []
    for each_string in initial_strings:
        lowercase_strings.append(each_string.lower())
    return lowercase_strings


def remove_uscore(strings):
    """Remove '_' from strings in list"""
    without_uscore_strings = []
    for each_string in strings:
        without_uscore_strings.append(each_string.replace("_", ""))
    return without_uscore_strings


def add_space(strings):
    """Add question mark to each list element"""
    space_strings = []
    for each_string in strings:
        space_strings.append(each_string + " ")
    return space_strings

## Call functions on our data one after another
initial_strings = ["_HELLO_", "there_", ",", "yOU", "ar_e", "Ah", "b_old", "1"]

lcased = lowercase_all(initial_strings)
lcased_removed_uscore = remove_uscore(lcased)
lcased_removed_uscore_add_space = add_space(lcased_removed_uscore)

print(lcased_removed_uscore_add_space)
## ['hello ', 'there ', ', ', 'you ', 'are ', 'ah ', 'bold ', '1 ']

R

Functional Style

Functional programming is an approach to solving problems taking into account some key principles:

  • Immutability

Data isnt changed once it is created - a new variable can be made but existing ones are not altered.

  • High order functions

Functions that can take other functions as arguments are used to break up parts of a problem. We will see an example using the map() and X functions below.

  • Function purity

Purity means that a function doesnt interact with the rest of the program. The function has no side effects - it doesnt alter other variables or objects outside itself.

In addition, pure functions when given the same input - always give the same output.


The principles of functional programming help when we convert our scripts into functions and then modules, improving our codes usability.

Python

## Define functions to perform each action
def lowercase(string):
    """Lowercase a string"""
    lowercase_string = string.lower()
    return lowercase_string
    
def remove_underscore(string):
    """Remove underscore from a string"""
    no_underscore_string = string.replace("_", "")
    return no_underscore_string
    
def add_space(string):
    """Add space to end of string"""
    added_space_string = string + " "
    return added_space_string
    
    
## Apply the functions across each element of the data
strings = ["_HELLO_", "there_", ",", "yOU", "ar_e", "Ah", "b_old", "1"]

# `map()` takes a function and an iterable, applying the function
# to each element of the iterable

lcased = map(lowercase, initial_strings)
lcased_removed_uscore = map(remove_underscore, lcased)
# Convert the last map object to a list
lcased_removed_uscore_add_space = map(add_space, lcased_removed_uscore)


print(list(lcased_removed_uscore_add_space))
## ['hello ', 'there ', ', ', 'you ', 'are ', 'ah ', 'bold ', '1 ']

In python there are a range of other parts of the language to help with functional programming:

  • List comprehensions
  • Map, Filter, Reduce
  • Lambda Functions
  • functools built-in module

R

Comparison

Each style has its appropriate uses, often in combination with each other.

Throughout this course we will try to design our code as functions following a functional principles. Each of the new code styles shown rely on use breaking our scripts up into functions appropriatly.

Scripts to Functions

In this section we will discuss considerations when converting scripts to functions. In this section we will use an example script to show the steps involved structuring code.

Example Analysis Code

The code that has been given to you by your colleague is given in this section. At present it is a script which is well commented, but not well structured. Your task is to structure the code allowing for future reproducible analysis.

At a high level the code:

  • Loads in the two data sets
  • Cleans the data
  • Joins the data so all useful information is together
  • Calculates an aggregate statistic
  • Tidies the output data
  • Writes the data to a csv file

Have a read through the script you have received, be sure to look up any sections you are not comfortable with.

If you would prefer to look at it within an IDE it is located in /course_content/example_code/initial_script/.

Python and R versions of the code are available.

Python

# File to analyse the mean population density data from the UN

# Import relevant libraries for analysis
import pandas as pd

# Load the population density data 2019
pop_density = pd.read_csv("../../../data/population_density_2019.csv")

# Clean the column names, following naming conventions similar to PEP8
pop_density.columns = pop_density.columns.str.lower()
pop_density.columns = pop_density.columns.str.replace(" ", "_")

# The country_and_parent_code column needs to 
# be split into two columns without the strings
pop_density[["country_code", "parent_code"]] = (pop_density["country_and_parent_code"]
                                                .str.split("_", expand=True))

# Remove the country_and_parent_code and parent_code columns, not used in later analysis
# axis=1 to remove the columns
pop_density = pop_density.drop(labels=[
                                       "country_and_parent_code", 
                                       "parent_code"
                                       ], 
                               axis=1)

# Convert country_code to integer by removing strings
pop_density["country_code"] = pop_density["country_code"].str.replace("CC", "")
pop_density["country_code"] = pop_density["country_code"].astype(int)


# Load the locations data to get the Sustainable Development Goals sub regions
locations = pd.read_csv("../../../data/locations.csv")

# Clean the column names, following naming conventions similar to PEP8
locations.columns = locations.columns.str.lower()
locations.columns =  locations.columns.str.replace(" ", "_")

# The location_id data has quotation marks making it a string,
# it needs to be converted to a numeric
locations["location_id"] = locations["location_id"].str.replace('"', '')
locations["location_id"] = locations["location_id"].astype(int)

# Join the data sets
# Left merge so we keep all pop_density data
pop_density_location = pop_density.merge(locations, 
                                         how="left",
                                         left_on="country_code",
                                         right_on="location_id")

# Remove the location_id column as it is equal to country_code or missing
pop_density_location = pop_density_location.drop(labels=["location_id"], axis=1)

# Get just the relevant columns in preparation
# for the following groupby
region_density = pop_density_location[["sdg_region_name", "population_density"]]

# Calculate the mean population density for each region
# A non-weighted mean
region_mean_density = (region_density.groupby('sdg_region_name', as_index=False)
                       .agg({"population_density": "mean"}))
                       
region_mean_density = region_mean_density.rename(columns={"population_density": "mean_population_density"})

# Sort the data for clearer reading
region_mean_density = region_mean_density.sort_values(by="mean_population_density",
                                                      ascending=False)

# Round mean density for clearer reading
region_mean_density["mean_population_density"] = region_mean_density["mean_population_density"].round(2)

# Write out the final output
region_mean_density.to_csv("mean_population_density_output.csv", index=False)

Output data:

Grouping code by functionality

Chunks of code that do similar things should be grouped together.

Deciding which sections of code make sense as being part of the same function is a common challenge when structuring code.

In order to convert code into a function - the main thing we look for is that it achieves one task. This means that the function does one thing. It may take us a few lines of code to achieve this one task - but the point is the function has a specific purpose.

When we write scripts we often repeat the same tasks at different points in the script. These are a prime parts of code to start converting into functions, is they reduce the amount of code written in the file - and make whats happening clearer.

If a code block isnt repeated throughout the code thats okay too - all the code can be converted to functions to be called one after the other.

Some code is often very similar with just a variable or two difference in different areas of the code. When reading the code its important to think about what is happening to the variables and data involved, and whether a similar process is happening elsewhere.


Returning to our example script, we are going to take one task, convert it into a function, then improve the function so it can be used multiple times.

The lines of code:

  • Load in a data frame given a path
  • Reformat the column names of the data frame

Initial Code

Python

# Load the population density data 2019
pop_density = pd.read_csv("../../../data/population_density_2019.csv")

pop_density.columns =  pop_density.columns.str.replace(" ", "_")

R

Basic Function

We can wrap the code into a function so that all the code can be run with one command like so.

Python

def load_formatted_pop_frame()
    """Read population data and reformat column names"""
    # Load the population density data 2019
    pop_density = pd.read_csv("../../../data/population_density_2019.csv")
    
    # Clean the column names, following naming conventions similar to PEP8
    pop_density.columns = pop_density.columns.str.lower()
    pop_density.columns = pop_density.columns.str.replace(" ", "_")
    
    return pop_density
    
population_density = load_formatted_pop_frame()

R

Adding Parameters

To improve the function we can add as an argument something which may change in the future - the path of the data string.

Consider how you would have to change the previous function if the location of the population_denisty_2019.csv file changed location.

It is important to make sure that our variable names should reflect accurated what variables they will hold. If we dont know exactly what data the variable will hold then we should use more generic placeholder names. These placeholder names should reflect what the variable is representing, not specific values.

When we add an argument to a function replacing a value within, we need to be sure to change all times that original variable was used.

In addtion, our comments should reflect the changes made too.

Python

The new function can now be used for both the population_density data and locations.csv.

def load_formatted_frame(path_to_data)
    """Read csv and reformat column names"""
    # Load the csv from given path
    dataframe = pd.read_csv(path_to_data)
    
    # Clean the column names, following naming conventions similar to PEP8
    dataframe.columns = dataframe.columns.str.lower()
    dataframe.columns = dataframe.columns.str.replace(" ", "_")
    
    return dataframe

# The path can be updated where the function is run if needed
population_density = load_formatted_frame("../../../data/population_density_2019.csv")

# The same function is used to load a formatted locations.csv
locations = load_formatted_frame("../../../data/locations.csv")

R

The new function can now be used for both the population_density data and locations.csv.

Scope

Scope is a very important concept when it comes to creating functions and structuring code.

Scope refers to the places in a program that a variable can be accessed.


When writing scripts variables can be accessed anywhere in the script - so long as the variable has been created already.

When we write scripts we are storing all our variables at the highest, most accessible area of the program. This is referred to as Global Scope.

Variables with global scope are accessible in all locations of the program.

This is the easiest way to store variables when learning to program - but it is something we want to avoid where possible.

On the other hand, some variables can only be accessed in certain locations within a program. When this happens it is referred to as Local Scope.
